{"/service/ndnp/mimtptc/batch_mimtptc_jerome_ver02/data/77618337/00414188199/1945080601/0001.xml":{"full_text":"The Newspaper of the Industry\nSparks\nReports say ODT regional officers\npect to be out of jobs Oct. 15.\nLet\u2019s hope they\u2019re right.\n4h\n45,000 Planet\n\u00abArmy Air Force says it will do\nare at least 45,000 military air\nolanes fit for surplus disposal by\nAe end of 1945.\n\nfor the Car\ncase of locking the door\nbefore you get the horsepower in:\nGM's Rochester division an\nnounces it is in production of locks\nand keys for those new models.\nmk\nTruck-Tire Boost\nTruck-tire expansion projects now\nearing completion will add 2,000,-\n000 heavy duty tires to the indus\n#y's yearly capacity, according to\nW. James Sears, deputy director of\n'VPB's rubber bureau.\nW\n50 c c Synthetic\nthan half of all the esti\nmated 100 million automobile wheels\n?re now rolling on synthetic rubber,\noimes J. Newman, vice-president of\nB. F. Goodrich, said last week.\nbased the estimate on a\nJRirvey taking into account recap\nping as well as new-tire sales for\n\u2022he last 20 months.\nW\nSpeed Demons\nJla call for speed .demons was\nIssued lust week by the Museum of\nScience and Industry in Chicago,\nxjrhe daredevils are wanted as driv\ners of old-time cars for the re-\nof the first auto race\n*ov. 28.\nBarney Oldfield, Ralph De Palma.\nHartz, Wilbur Shaw, are you\nlistening?\n\nSuperman uilh Wings\nThe world\u2019s fastest airplane, the\nAt-propelled P-80 Shooting Star,\nzoomed out from under Army cen\nsorship last week.\nfi Built by Lockheed, the fighter\nas a speed of more than 550 mph\ni\u00bbnd a ceiling topping 45,000 feet.\nConvertible into a fighter-bomber\nfar superior to any Nazi buzz bomb,\nShooting Star is said to stage\n\u2122s best performance using kerosene\nas fuel.\nt\nProfit Jolts Cut\nBusiness profits and war workers'\ncomes will be reduced in the new\nfiscal year by a 20-billion-dollar\nAnsh in government war spending,\naccording to the Budget bureau.\nIf V-J Day comes before next\nthere will be an even\ngreater cutback in U. S. expendi\ntures. The extent: of unemployment\nC such a case would be determined\nby the scope and effectiveness of\nplans.\nW\n/Vnsi Veil Lifted\njpMore than 200 American tech\nnical experts are now in Europe\nJjvestigating Germany\u2019s industrial\nCar secrets, Foreign Economic Ad\nministrator Leo T. Crowley, has\nwinounced.\n\u2122The technicians are under orders\nto search out German industrial\nfrocesses, inventions, engineering\nnd \"know-how\u201d required to aid\nU. S. war production. Procedures\nnow being established for the\nwider dissemination of the infor\nmation as soon as practicable.\nIn This Issue\nbrairr Doing* Pus 12\nAlrrrmft New* Pnge IS\nFOB Fortory Pms\u00ab 14\nNew WPB Role\nIn Reconversion\nIs Indicated\nMoves Hint Agencies\n\\re (wetting Set for\nPossible Early Peace\nWASHINGTON. Action\nwas reported to be in the\nworks last week to put gov\nernment agencies in position\nto speed reconversion should\nJapan surrender soon.\nFears have been expressed that\nan early surrender would catch the\nnation short on reconversion. The\neconomy would suffer and the post\nwar boom be delayed.\nOne step was reported to be a\nrecommendation to President\nTruman by John W. Snyder, war\nand reconversion mobilizer, that\nWPB\u2019s operations be extended to\ncover the field of reconversion.\nAnother is the contemplated\nmerger, believed to be months\naway, of the Office of War Mobili\nzation and Reconversion and the\nOffice of Economic Stabilization.\n\"Vlf the first step is taken, WPB\nwould be able to use its broad war\ntime priority powers to break bot\ntlenecks which might impede a\nrapid return to high-level civilian\nproduction.\"\nThus WPB would operate as an\narm of Snyder\u2019s OWMR.\nSuch action w.ould be contrary\nto WPB\u2019s announced intentions,\nhowever. J. A. Krug, WPB chief,\nhas asserted that with few reser\nvations to protect production for\nthe Pacific War and small busi\nness, industry would be given its\nhead in the reconversion period.\nIndustry would get little priority\naid, and individual companies\nwould be on their own in getting\ntheir share of what free materials\nwere available.\nHowever, the possibility of a\nquick end to the Pacific war might\nnecessitate action to prevent chaos\nin industry.\nBehind the new proposals may be\nthe furor created by the report\nearlier in the week of the Senate\n(Mead) War Investigating commit\ntee. The report charged that gov\nernment confusion and Army man\npower waste have so retarded new\ncar production that the industry\nwon't be able to reach its full out\nput speed until October, 1947.\nMeanwhile, the charge of military\ninterference was supported by\nLester P. Doidge, former chief of\nthe consumer durable goods branch\nof WPB\u2019s Office of Civilian Re\nquirements. He said that the armed\n(See WPB, Page 8, Col. 5)\nNEGOTIATIONS FOB PI RCHASE of the loot two 1\u00bb42 automobile* both\nexpen*ive matom-bnilt model*, in stock of the Detroit branch of the Packard\nMotor Far C\u2019o. have Ju*t been completed with a representative of the Russian\ngovernment. Sale of the car* to I. I. Kariov, chief automotive-tractor depart\nment of the government purchasing commission of the Soviet Union In the\nF. S. A., was completed by S. P. Rockwell, pictured above with the last two\nK rewar models. The cars are \u201c1M\u201d seven-passenger Packard sedans with bodv\ny I\u00abe\u00dfaron. They are being readied in Detroit for shipment to\u2019 New York\nwhere they will be exported to Russia for personal nse of high-rankfar\ngovernment officials.\nDETROIT, AUGUST 6, 1945\n359 Ntnc Ford Cars\nProduced in July\nDEARBORN.\u2014Ford produced\n559 new can in July and has\n4,000 scheduled for August, with\nmore assembly plants coming\nInto operation. September\u2019s\nschedule calls for 7,000. In addi\ntion, 5,889 new trucks were pro\nduced. Tw ice as many are sched\nuled in August.\nTimetable for the other assem\nbly plants calls for Edgewatcr,\nX. J., to come in Aug. IS; Louis\nville, Aug. 16; Dallas, Aug. 20\n(tentative), and Buffalo, Sept, t\n(tentative).\nStout Car Due\nTo Join Kaiser,\nFrazer in \u201946\nDETROIT.\u2014A third automobile,\ndesigned by William B. Stout, will\nbe introduced some time in 1946,\nit was announced last week by\nJoseph W. Frazer, president of\nGraham Paige and of Kaiscr-\nFrazer Corp.\nThe car, reported to be six\nmonths along in development, is\nexpected to embody many of Stout\u2019s\nprevious ideas, including a rear\nengine. It is likely that it will sell\nin the medium-price range.\nFrazer\u2019s announcement said the\nStout car will he in production\n\u201ca little later\u201d than the Kaiser\nand Fraser cars which are slated\nfor next spring. But his state\nment did not make clear whether\nthe Stout ear will be an offering\nof Kaiser-Fraser or of Graham-\nI'aige only.\nUnder the rsCe nt 1 y formed\nKaiscr-Frazer Corp., Graham-Paige\nowns 50 percent of the new corpo\nration but retains its entity. Furth\nermore, Stout, who is on loan from\nConsolidated-Vultee Aircraft Corp.,\nis strictly a Graham man. indicat\ning that the Stout car will be a\nspecial Graham offering, or the\nnucleus of another company.\nSuch a thing would further com\nplicate the dealer picture. Frazer\n(See STOUT. Pa\u00bb:e 32. Col. 1)\nNew Surplus Office\nDetroit Branch Is Set Up to Overcome Dealer\nObjections on Parts Sales\nBy Jack Weed\nService Editor\nDETROIT.\u2014A new Detroit office\nof the Department of Commerce is\nbeing established through which all\ninformation to the trade on Ord\nnance surplus automotive parts\nand their sale will be channelled.\nIt will be known as the Surplus\nAutomotive Parts Office and J. J.\nOsborne, of the Washington office\nNADA Figures Debunk\nFallacy That Dealers\nCan Stand Discount Cut\nAverage Yearly Earnings Only 1.07 Percent Compared\nWith 14% for Manufacturers OP A Told;\nSSR 49 Due for Drastic Revision\nBy Mel Adams\nStaff Correspondent\nCHICAGO.\u2014William L. Mallon, president of NADA, un\nloosed a bombshell at a meeting of the OPA retail motor\nvehicle advisory committee here last week when he presented\nfacts and figures compiled to prove the inadvisability of\ncutting dealer discounts on new cars. He showed that dealers\u2019\nannual earnings average only\n1.07 percent as compared with\n14 percent for manufacturers.\nAnother highlight of the two-day\nconference at the Stevens hotel was\na revelation by Clark D. Moody,\nhead of the general services section\nof OPA, that an amendment to\nRegulation 49 is in the making and\nis expected to be adopted (sec\nSparks column today). No plan for\nextension beyond Sept. 30 is con\ntemplated, he added.\nRationing of now cars now in\nproduction and to be built came to\nthe fore aiso, with agreement that\nrationing should be picked up\nwhere it left off on 1942 models, but\nwith flexibility enough to broaden\nthe eligibility list as fast as pro\nduction permits.\nThe 15 members of the commit\ntee and OPA officials in attend\nance discussed the lack of au\nthority for dealers to use the first\nof their new cars for display anil\ndemonstrator purposes, instead of\nfor sale to buyers. OPA has made\nno ruling on this point and deal\ners, it was felt by the committee,\nshould have the right to retain\nthe first cars for their floor and\ndemonstrating.\nAlso on the agenda were discus\n(.Contlnued on I\u2019aise 33. Col. 1\nof Department of Commerce, was\nin the city last week setting up\nthe office. W. P. Baughman will\nbe in charge.\nWashington has realized for\nsome time that the manner in\nwhich surplus automotive parts\nwere being offered to the trade\nwas not meeting with trade ac\nceptance. Formation of this new\nDetroit office, which will be the\nexclusive handling point of all\nautomotive surplus parts sales, is\nthe Department of Commerce\u2019s\nanswer to the problem.\nFunction of this office will be to\nproperly catalog and describe all\nimportant lots of parts that are\noffered for sale to automotive deal\ners and wholesalers, so that buyers\nwill not only have an accurate de\nscription of the parts and their\ncondition but will be furnished the\nnames of the vehicles in which the\nvarious parts can be <used. This\nfunction is seen as being necessary\nto interest the larger dealers and\nwholesalers in the trade and make\nit possible for them to judge more\naccurately the condition and worth\nof each lot of parts offered for sale.\nIn the past, considerable confu\nsion has arisen regarding the con\ndition of surplus automotive parts\noffered, due principally to a lack\nof information as to where and\ni**\u00ab BURPLUB. 29. Col\n$4 Per Y ear, 15e Per Copy\nThe\nNo Change in\nDealer Discount\nTOLEDO.-The Wlllya Jeep will\nlist at $1,090, FOB Toicdo, Charles\nE. Sorenson, president of Willys-\nOverland, revealed here last week.\n(This is only $35 less than the\nprice predicted by Automotive News\ntwo weeks previously.)\nOPA announced that ceiling\nprices for sales by the manufac\nturer to distributors and dealers\nand by distributors to dealers are\nestablished on a dollar-and-cent\nbasis. These prices reflect the\ncustomary trade disrounts given\nto resellers hy manufacturers.\nWith the attachments, which are\nnecessary to make the Jeep a\n\"universal farm vehicle,\u201d the price\nruns over $1,500.\nAdditions which may be made to\nthe $1,090 price include the federal\nexcise tax of $46.53, transportation\nfrom factory to dealer at rail car\nload rate, charges up to S2O for\npreparing and conditioning for de\nlivery, and any state or local taxes.\nThe dealer may add also the fol\nlowing prices for optional equip\nment:\nFront body top. $51.05; rear body\ntop, $28.44; draw bar (for hauling\nother vehicles or farm machinery),\n$6.91; governor (to limit maximum\nspeed of the vehicle) $27.21; heater,\n$17.41; pintle hook (for use when\nthe jeep is used us a power plant\nin hoisting operations), $4.01; pow\ner take-off (attachment for con\nverting jeep\u2019s motor for use as a\nstationary engine), $90.67; power\ntake off attachment for front,\n$24.44; power take-off shield for\nfront, $1.93; pulley and pulley drive\nrear (for use in pulling stumps,\nand with lifting or pulling tackle),\n$56.28; radiator brush guard, $4.11;\nan additional front bucket type\npassenger seat (the basic car comes\ndelivered with a single bucket-type\nseat for driver), $10.51; rear pas\nsenger seat (for two persons),\n$12.96; spare tire and tube, $13.76.\nThese items of equipment are sub\nject to Federal excise taxes, which\nthe seller may add to the purchase\nprice.\n(.ivilian Truck Output\n111,318 in Half\nWASHINGTON.\u2014WPB reports\nfirst six months total truck pro\nduction of 410,094 units as against\n398,951 for last half of 1944. Of\nthis year\u2019s first half output, 111,-\n318 units were for non-military\nuse, including 17,658 light, 68465\nmedium and 25,006 heavy tracks.\nFirst half truck-trailer produc\ntion is reported at 97J11 as\nagainst 77,669 units for the last\n1 half of 1944.","height":"18936","width":"13839"}}
